  "text": "This latter proposal prompts consideration of a further difference between the human and animal experimental procedures that was not discussed by [CITATION_1] . It is that the human participants are routinely instructed to look for differences between the stimuli during preexposure. For example, in the experiment by [CITATION_2] , the subjects received the following instructions: \"In [. . .] this experiment you will see some colored grids [. . .] Please examine them carefully. The grids are very similar but some of them have small differences. Please try to find these differences\" [CITATION_3] , p. 2087 . Such instructions can be expected to enhance the rewarding properties of detecting a unique feature and might thus promote the development of an appropriate attentional response and of a perceptual learning effect. In the absence of instructions, the effect might be reduced or even absent. The present experiments were designed to test this idea.",
